```

In this example, if the `userId` is greater than 100, we send a 404 Not Found status along with a message. If the `userId` is less than 0, we send a 500 Internal Server Error. Otherwise, we send a 200 OK status (which is the default) along with the user ID.

It's also good practice to send an informative message along with the status code to help the client understand what went wrong. This is often done using the `res.send()` or `res.json()` methods.

By using appropriate status codes and error responses, you can make your web applications more robust and easier to debug, providing a better experience for both users and developers.

